<div id="review_1506847958" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1506847958" />
    <a title="David J" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6494653-david-j"><img alt="David J" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613787566p2/6494653.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1506847958?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David J" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David J" href="/user/show/6494653-david-j">David J</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6494653-david-j?shelf=japanese">japanese</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6494653-david-j?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6494653-david-j?shelf=purchased-2016">purchased-2016</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6494653-david-j?shelf=my-library">my-library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6494653-david-j?shelf=in-translation">in-translation</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1506847958" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18000316516068398879">I first came by Ryūnosuke Akutagawa via Akira Kurosawa’s 1950 film <i>Rashōmon</i>. It’s an adaptation of two short stories within this collection: “In a Bamboo Grove” and “Rashōmon” (though Kurosawa adapted the former and simply took the name of the latter and used it as a framing device). It’s one of my favorite Kurosawa films, and so I knew I’d like to check out the source material at some point. I’m glad I did, because there are some really good stories here and it’s an overall well-rounded antholo</span>
  <span id="freeText18000316516068398879" style="display:none">I first came by Ryūnosuke Akutagawa via Akira Kurosawa’s 1950 film <i>Rashōmon</i>. It’s an adaptation of two short stories within this collection: “In a Bamboo Grove” and “Rashōmon” (though Kurosawa adapted the former and simply took the name of the latter and used it as a framing device). It’s one of my favorite Kurosawa films, and so I knew I’d like to check out the source material at some point. I’m glad I did, because there are some really good stories here and it’s an overall well-rounded anthology.<br /><br />This collection is divided into four sections: A World in Decay, Under the Sword, Modern Tragicomedy, and Akutagawa's Own Story. Akutagawa crosses genres throughout these stories--from comedy to drama to autobiography to Jidaigeki to the Gothic--and a lot of them work out quite well. I’m a particular fan of “In a Bamboo Grove,” “Hell Screen,” “The Nose,” “The Spider Thread,” and “Green Onions.” The autobiographical stories in the last section, while at times quite fascinating in learning about Akutagawa’s inner turmoil, don’t read as well as the previous stories; they’re interesting and informational, but they’re ultimately a little hard to get into and not as entertaining as the previous stories.<br /><br />Akutagawa is a great writer. He oftentimes has some slick and inviting prose, which makes for easy and enjoyable reading. His well-placed comedic touches were surprising too. However, if you aren’t that educated on Japanese history and geography, like me, then you may struggle a bit with the references. There are extremely helpful note indications throughout, but that means flipping to the back of the book, which does disrupt the flow of reading. I’d definitely recommend this collection, but some might want to proceed with caution.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18000316516068398879" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


